{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778696282,"nonce":"aOeZa4zCq6xVPTZ47seKzaQApYw=","message":"**`align_trials` primitive is now available upstream (`06f7faf`).**\n\nThe go-cue alignment fix on `06f7faf` added a shared helper:\n```\nfrom rlrmp.analysis.trial_alignment import (\n    align_trials,           # generic re-lock per-trial event to a fixed column\n    replicate_mean_curves,  # per-replicate nanmean over aligned trials\n    pooled_trial_mean_with_band,  # pooled (replicate, trial) mean + SD/SEM band\n)\n```\n\nFor the early-vs-late go-cue stratification proposed in this issue, the most direct usage will be:\n1. Compute `aligned, center = align_trials(v_fwd, go_idx)` once on the eval batch.\n2. Stratify by quantile/median split on `go_idx` (e.g. `mask_early = go_idx \u003c np.median(go_idx)`).\n3. Apply the same aggregation helpers to each stratum independently for the figure.\n4. Reuse `align_trials` again for the *absolute-time* counterpart figure by passing `idx = np.zeros_like(go_idx)` (or simply not calling `align_trials` and keeping the raw absolute-time profiles) — the issue body proposes side-by-side go-aligned vs absolute-time-since-target-onset plots.\n\nThe fix on `06f7faf` is upstream of this work — the stratification analysis can now build on the same primitive used by the corrected production figures, ensuring consistent semantics.\n\n`align_trials` accepts a generic alignment index (not specifically go), so a future variant of this analysis that aligns to *target onset* would just pass the target-onset column from `trial_specs.timeline.epoch_bounds` instead of column 2 (the go cue). No code change needed in the helper itself.","files":null}]}